{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641982"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:35:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:35:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17923"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17923"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.94,0,0,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10637"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74974"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10637"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60480"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"2947"},{"type":"tags","id":"3504"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24781"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74974"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old male presented to his General Practitioner with lethargy, weight loss and polyuria. His blood glucose level was 22.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following symptoms is most consistent with a diagnosis of type 1 diabetes mellitus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Polyuria","Weight gain","Constipation","Abdominal pain","Fatigue"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolyuria\u003C/strong\u003E is a classic symptom of type 1 diabetes mellitus (T1D) due to osmotic diuresis caused by hyperglycaemia. The kidneys excrete excess glucose in the urine, leading to increased urine output.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeight gain\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with the initial presentation of T1D. Instead, patients often experience weight loss due to the body\u0027s inability to utilise glucose effectively, leading to the breakdown of fat and muscle for energy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConstipation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a common symptom of T1D. Gastrointestinal symptoms are more often associated with other conditions or complications of diabetes, such as gastroparesis, which occurs later in the disease course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal pain\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in T1D, particularly if diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is present, but it is not a primary symptom of the disease itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFatigue\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-specific symptom that can be associated with many conditions, including T1D, due to the lack of glucose utilisation for energy. However, it is not as specific as polyuria for the diagnosis of T1D.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type 1 diabetes mellitus often presents with polyuria, polydipsia, and weight loss due to hyperglycaemia and osmotic diuresis.","Weight gain is not a typical symptom of type 1 diabetes mellitus at presentation."],"references":["DiMeglio LA, Evans-Molina C, Oram RA. Type 1 diabetes. Lancet. 2018 Jun 16;391(10138):2449-2462. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31320-5. PMID: 29916386; PMCID: PMC6661119","Lucier J, Mathias PM. Type 1 Diabetes. 2024 Oct 5. 